\par \tab Gleick provides a colorful analysis.  It indicates that an automatic self-destruct mechanism exploded the vehicle, and that the payload was uninsured.  The self-destruct mechanism operated because the vehicle had gon
e aerodynamically unstable and the boosters were being ripped from the rocket.  
\par \tab It turns out that the guidance system received undecipherable data from the inertial platform software and }{\b\f1\fs28\cf1 the arithmetic error was detected by the software}{\f1\fs28\cf1 .  The problem was
 that the error message, which was undecipherable and misinterpreted by the rest of the system, was not part of the expected behavior.  In addition, }{\b\f1\fs28\cf1 there was a redundant system on board}{\f1\fs28\cf1 
, but it was there for hardware, not software failure: it ran the same software and failed the same way.  In fact, the backup system failed milliseconds before the live system.
\par \tab Finally, this software had run successfully before, and the limitation was known.  But }{\b\f1\fs28\cf1 at the time of its design into Ariane 4, the velocities at which the overflow would occur were not attainable.}{\f1\fs28\cf1 
  With Ariane 5, they were attainable and they did attain.
\par \tab The most exciting part of the fiasco is that the failing software "actually }{\b\f1\fs28\cf1 served no purpose once the rocket was in the air}{\f1\fs28\cf1 . Its only function was
 to align the system before launch."  The software was left running as a "feature" so that if there was a hold in the last few seconds of launch, the alignment wouldn't have to be started up again.
\par \tab Although Gleick finds the Board of Inquiry report rather dry, as a demonstration of software forensics it is marvelous and very pertinent to the work of the class this week [Lions1996].
