\par \tab The self-destruction of the vehicle was not computer directed or directed by ground controllers.  It was an automatic arrangement upon the severing of electrical connections between the boosters and the main veh
icle.  This was designed-in behavior and it operated properly.
\par \tab The analysis of the explosion discovered a hydraulic pressure anomaly that was unrelated to the failure but that was pointed out to be addressed before any further Ariane 5 flights.
\par \tab The softw
are that failed was written in Ada, and arithmetic errors were protected by exceptions.  Unfortunately, because this particular exception was thought to be impossible and to arise only as a hardware failure, there was no software to catch the exception an
d provide some benign outcome.
\par \tab The analysis indicates that diagnostic data (because of the number conversion) was being reported by the inertial reference system, and the control computer was incorrectly interpreting the diagnostic messages as flight data.
  The inertial platform system was designed to shut down on unprotected exception and it did. There was no risk analysis for the inappropriateness of such a shutdown being the consequence of a software failure and hence threatening the entire guidance ope
ration of a mission.
\par \tab The fact that the software was even running was totally unnecessary any time after lift-off.
\par \tab None of the QA, testing, and simulation methodologies allowed for anything but random hardware failures.  There was no consideration of possi
ble software failures, and the inertial platform system was considered correct until proven to have failed.  For this reason, the inertial platform system was not included in simulations of flight conditions for Ariane 5 missions.
